  "prompt": "Now that India has banned 500 & 1000 notes, what will people with excess of such notes accrued as black money do? Can they still escape?",
  "response": "The demonetization of \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes by the Indian government in November 2016 aimed to curb black money, counterfeit currency, and corruption. Individuals holding large amounts of these notes had several options, though each came with risks:\n\n1. **Deposit in Banks:** Initially, people were allowed to deposit the old notes into bank accounts. However, this posed a risk of scrutiny by tax authorities, especially if the amount was substantial.\n\n2. **Exchange:** There was a window for exchanging old notes for new currency, but similar to deposits, larger transactions could raise suspicion.\n\n3. **Utilization in Transactions:** Some might have attempted to spend their old notes quickly in a bid to avoid detection, particularly in big transactions like purchasing assets.\n\n4. **Conversion into Other Assets:** Some people may have sought to convert cash into gold, real estate, or other forms of investment to safeguard their wealth. \n\n5. **Bribery and Corruption:** In some cases, individuals might have engaged in bribery or corruption to convert notes unofficially.\n\nDespite these avenues, the demonetization effort led to significant challenges for those with unaccounted wealth. Authorities increased surveillance and investigations into large deposits and spending patterns, leading to arrests and penalties for tax evasion.\n\nWhile some individuals may have found ways to escape scrutiny, the broad effects of demonetization disrupted many avenues for sustaining black money. In the long run, it encouraged individuals and businesses to maintain more transparent financial practices to avoid legal repercussions.",
